* We use 2 Million as our margin of error because videos that do not chart on Youtube video can have as much as 4M to 5M undetected ad-promoted views, so half of that value seems a good compromise.
Whenever Youtube Charts are available for a video, that estimate is used.
Not all videos are available in Youtube Charts if the video doesn't reach the top 100 of the week (which caps about 4M to 5M weekly). This means a video that have 3M non-organic views and 1M real views will not chart, and therefore we cannot compare our estimate with Youtube Charts.

Precision: The average difference from the correct value.

Wouldn't it be true to say that a view is a view, regardless of why people watched it?
Yes, even the views counted when the videos are watched as an advertisement have to obbey Youtube rules (minimal time watched or engagement). However, Organic views are willful, and people watched because they wanted. Meanwhile, Ad-views are imposed by the system and most time they play out because they are part of a playlist of people without Youtube Premium. For instance, a TV on a bar with a K-Pop playlist will show all ads since nobody will skip them.
Therefore, organic views represent people really watching because they are interested in the content, while non-organic views are not initiated by people and for one reason or other they didn't skop, but in no way it means people wanted, liked or engaged with it. It can be easily proved by how rare (nearly never) an ad-promoted view generates a like and, as such, how well the View per Like algorithm works.
Where is the "View Behaviour" method that used to pair with the "View per Like" method?
The View Behaviour method is now embeded in the main algorithm, and therefore is used to tweak the estimates, although to a lesser degree.
Why did you stop using the algorithm and decided to focus on Youtube Charts method?
Even though our algorithm is close to 90% correct, people have a strong sense that Mathematics is flawded and imprecise and Youtube Charts are always true. After years trying to teach people why Statistics and Probability works, it became easier to go with the mob mentality that Youtube is always correct and Math isn't, so now we use Youtube as the main source and only use the algorithm to complement missing data. This move was only to stop our spam mail and hate comments and does not mean we think Youtube is trustworthy in their charts.
If you understand Stat&prob and would like to see the Algorithm take on the NOV of a video, simply look at the daily graphic displayed on a MV. Since Youtube does not have Daily charts, that data is still based all on our algorithm, but is not used on the total if Youtube Chart data is available.
Why don't you trust Youtube? What do they have to say?
After several videos charting incorrectly, we tried to contact Youtube only to get our question deleted after 2000 upvotes, when we insisted, they just banned us from the support forum. Data remains incorrect in Youtube Charts, so not only they are not turstworthy, they also exibit signs of a purposeful agenda. You can see a screenshot of my original question here. HOWEVER, due to people's perception that statistics is flawded and Youtube is perfect, we decided since March 2023 to actually use Youtube Charts as our main source to avoid headache trying to explain Math to people.
Why the estimates change from day to day?
As more Youtube Charts data is released (weekly), and as more daily NOV are calculated in the interval by our algorithm to fill the gaps while a new Youtube Chart hasn't been released, the estimates might change daily on the first 4~5 weeks.
Do estimated non-organic views shown at this site reflect the actual number of "artificial" (non-organic) views in a MV?
Obviously not. These are based on mathematic estimates by Statistics and probabilty, and Youtube Chart not-so-trustworthy data. They are just for reference, but are not hard proff. Notice, however, we get very close to the 'confirmed' Youtube Chart with our algorithm.

Why views stop for a while on the first day of some MVs?
It happens at any time when too many people are watching it, and also due to server caching, where you get old (but faster) data until the server updates it again. On the first day, it is aggravated by the fact that after a few hundred views, Youtube starts auditing views to catch bots, which makes it use cache more often since it will audit suspicious IPs. Views do not stop counting, they are still ongoing, it is just that Youtube will not update the available information that often.

Do Youtube deduct, return or adds views in videos?
No, never without reason. Youtube can deduct some views from IPs it recognized as bots (it would be visible as negative growth or a big one-day dip in the view number in a given period). This is no longer as visible for a few years because Youtube rather adjust views in time and not causing negative views. Youtube does not "return" views or likes (it doesn't have any feature to even store data that can be "returned"), and while it certainly does not add views, you can get views from TrueView Ads (Youtube's own Advertising system) that can be paid for by anyone, not only the channel owner. In short: Youtube can deduct views perceived as bots, but it never adds views.

Why isn't a Music Video in this list? Will you update this?
This list is 100% automatic. Nobody inputs or changes this list manually. If a video is in the list, there are calculated NOVs for it. If a video is not on the list, the calculation did not show NOVs. Remember, these are estimates, values can be wrong, being or not on this list is not a hard proof of anything, just an estimate.
Can fans inflate the numbers of views by repeating non-stop a video?
Hardly. Youtube stops counting repeats from the same IP after a few views per day (the exact formula is unknown), and even if it didn't, it still requires you to play a meaningful size of the video to count as a new view. If we pretend Youtube counts all views, a person could repeat a video about 400 times a day, which is 2,800 per week. It would require more than 1,000 people doing that for a whole week to get 2.8M views. That is nothing compared to Promoted Views and Organic views, and we are still pretending Youtube will not stop counting repeats after a while (it certainly does).

Please don't do this, views are not meaningful, instead buy the song or stream them in real streaming services. Promote the artist, not the Music Video.
Can fans pay for views?
Yes, Fans can raise money and create a campaign using any eligible Youtube Video. It happens all the time, however it is rather expensive - therefore, big campaigns are usually done by the artist studio/company themselves. How do I know if Youtube considers a video as a Music Video?
Usually it is automatic, specially from official channels. If you want to manually confirm Youtube considers a video as a Music Video, check in the artist page in Youtube Music: all the Music Videos (often including Dance Practices and even some lives) will appear in the artist library.
Why Artist "A" is not on the list at all?
Because they have no estimated NOVs in any of their videos. Doesn't mean their studios or fans never promoted them though. Likewise, MVs that do have Non-organic views might somehow evade both our NOV estimates and not show. Also notice we only started analysing videos since June 2020.
